#Text=Australian activists break into Pine Gap spy facility
#Text=Saturday , December 10 , 2005
#Text=Australian Federal Police ( AFP ) have arrested six people following a breach of security at the secretive Pine Gap Joint Defence Facility in central Australia on Friday .

#Text=The members of the group Christians Against All Terrorism ( CAAT ) breached base security at dawn and two of them infiltrated two perimeter fences and scaled a building , before being arrested .
#Text=Two of the protesters photographed themselves atop a building inside the spy base .

#Text=A Northern Territory police spokeswoman said three men and two women had been charged over the incident while another woman would be summoned to appear in Alice Springs court next week over obstructing police .
#Text=The spokeswoman said the activists had allegedly cut holes in the external and internal fences at the defence facility .
#Text=She said the combined charges carried a maximum penalty of seven years jail .
#Text=The group claims it was the first break-in of its kind at Pine Gap .
#Text=The group spoke yesterday of their efforts to conceal a digital camera memory stick in the clothing of key members to avoid the images being confiscated by police .
#Text=Four of the protesters are from Queensland , one is from New South Wales , and the other is from Victoria .
#Text=They say they wanted to conduct a citizens inspection of the controversial Pine Gap facility .
#Text=" We could not allow the US and Australian governments to continue to conceal the role of Pine Gap in the ongoing war in Iraq , " said Sean O'Reilly of the group .
#Text=" It 's time the Australian public knew the reality of what is happening on our land . "
#Text=Group member Jessica Morrison claims there is a lot of secrecy surrounding the facility . "

column1: #Text=It was unclear last night whether the group would be charged under the Federal Government 's tough new anti-terror laws .
#Text=They were bailed to face the Alice Springs Magistrates Court next Wednesday .
